                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-213-off1208 t18291029-213-victim1763"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-213-person1764">
                  THOMAS 
                  SAUNDERS
               <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1764" type="surname" value="SAUNDERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1764" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1764" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18291029-213-viclabel1210" type="occupation">watchmaker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-213-victim1763 t18291029-213-viclabel1210"></join>, and keep a shop in <placeName id="t18291029-213-crimeloc1211">Whitechapel-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18291029-213-crimeloc1211" type="placeName" value="Whitechapel-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18291029-213-crimeloc1211" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-213-off1208 t18291029-213-crimeloc1211"></join>. On the 6th of October, between seven and eight o'clock in the morning, I was standin the parlour, and saw the prisoner with his hand in a little glass-case in the shop - he took out six knives; he came in from the street - I did not know him before; I ran to the door - he was taken by an officer, and brought back; the tray was deficient of six knives.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. Will you take upon yourself to swear the prisoner's arm was in the glass-case? A. Yes; I was six or eight feet from the place -I saw the prisoner in the shop, and he had his arms in the glass-case; he saw me, drew his arm back, and ran away - the prisoner is the person who took the knives - there were only this half dozen pen-knives; they were in the glass the night before, and the shop had not been opened, only the door - they were dropped at my door, and brought into my shop immediately; I never said the arm I saw in the glass-case I thought was my son's - I said I thought my son was in the shop, as I had just opened my street door, and then went into the parlour; at first I thought it was my son, but when I went to the door I saw she prisoner running - I was as quick in getting to the door as he was; it is a wide road.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-213-person1765">
                  ROBERT 
                  ROBERTS
               <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1765" type="surname" value="ROBERTS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1765" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1765" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in Whitechapel-road on the 6th of October, early in the morning; I saw the prisoner running, and some persons after him - I saw Mr. Thompson stop him; I saw some knives in the road a minute or two after I saw the prisoner in the - they were place over which he had run - I did not take them up till he was stopped.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Were there a great many people? A. No, only one or two running after him - he did not turn any corners.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-213-person1766">
                  ANTHONY 
                  THOMPSON
               <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1766" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1766" type="given" value="ANTHONY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1766" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner running, and secured him eighty or a hundred yards from the shop - he turned no corner; the knives were brought into the shop.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. My master sent me to a marine-store shop in the Dog-row, and told me to make haste - I was running, the witness came, and took hold of me; Mr. Thompson took me back, and began searching me - he asked the prosecutor if he had lost any thing; he said<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182910290084"></xptr>No, and asked his son where the two gold watches were - he said up stairs; a person brought in the knives, and then I was taken to the watch-house - the prosecutor there said he saw some person in his shop, and he thought it was his son exposing goods for sale; the Magistrate asked him if he saw me take the knives - he said No, but he saw my arm in the window; I asked him why he did not attack me at the moment - he said he thought it was his son; I asked him again, and he said he did not want to be asked any questions by me - the Magistrate said I must tell a Jury that story.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-213-person1767">
                  ANTHONY 
                  THOPSON
               <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1767" type="surname" value="THOPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1767" type="given" value="ANTHONY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1767" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. I believe he saw two persons in his shop and one ran one way and the other the other, and he thought one was his son - he first asked if the gold watches were safe; he did not then say any thing about his son.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-213-person1768">
                  THOMAS 
                  SAUNDERS
               <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1768" type="surname" value="SAUNDERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1768" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-person1768" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. Q. How long was it from first to last? A. I suppose not three minutes.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Were your shutters up? A. Yes, but the door was open, and it was sufficiently light for me to see the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18291029-213-verdict1212" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18291029-213-verdict1212" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 18.</p>
